<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12171n"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12171n">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12171n"> 171(n)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> <font face="wake">H</font> with ladder up ~</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">All that great congeries of ruins <font color="green">[in Glendalough]</font> dating from pre-Norman times speaks of a very large community. They are typical. There is the round tower, <i>cloigtheach</i>, a belfry, place of retreat into which the pious monks used to retire, <mark>drawing up the ladder after them</mark>; there is the big church with high-pitched roof of stone, and its galaxy of lesser chapels, just as in Ciaran&apos;s city of Clonmacnoise. <small> Stephen Gwynn, <a name="SGWL" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#SGWL"><cite title="source">Leinster</cite></a> (1911) 48</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c12172l" href="c12all.htm#c12172l">VI.C.12:172(l)</a></mm></dd> </dd></dl>
